<a name="ISA.isa2"></a>
<h2>The <strong>isa2</strong> R package</h2>

This package contains the core implementation of the ISA. If you do
not work with gene expression data, then this is the only package that
you need.

<h3>Download and installation</h3>

<p>
The <strong>isa2</strong> R package is available from the
Comprehensive R Archive Network, the standard repository of R
packages. The easiest way to install it is to type
<pre class="programlisting">
install.packages("isa2")
</pre>
in your R session. Please try it before downloading from here.
</p>

<ul class="download-links">
  <li class="download-windows">
    <a href="downloads/isa_$ISA_VERSION.zip">Microsoft Windows (all versions)</a><br/>
    Save this file, start R, and from
    the <code>Packages</code> menu choose <code>Install packages
      from local zip files</code>. Select the
    saved <code>isa_$ISA_VERSION.zip</code> file.
  </li>
  <li class="download-osx">
    <a href="downloads/isa_$ISA_VERSION.tgz">Mac OSX (all versions)</a><br/>
    Save this file. Then use
    the <b><code>install.packages()</code></b> function to install it;
    give the full path to the downloaded file (<code>isa_$ISA_VERSION.tgz</code>)
    instead of just the package name, and use
    the <code>repos=NULL</code> additional argument.
  </li>
  <li class="download-source">
    <a href="downloads/isa_$ISA_VERSION.tar.gz">Linux variants, Unix systems</a><br/>
    This is an R source package. Save this file. Then use
    the <b><code>install.packages()</code></b> function to install it;
    give the full path to the downloaded file
    (<code>isa_$ISA_VERSION.tar.gz</code>) instead of just the
    package name, and use the <code>repos=NULL</code> additional
    argument. You will need a C compiler to install this package.
  </li>
</ul>

